cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.SOC, cs.HC, cs.CL 

This paper focuses on the social and psychological aspects of social media use, particularly in relation to political polarization and echo chambers. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Additionally, the paper involves the use of a visualization tool and randomized experiment, which could fall under cs.CY (Computers and Society) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper also touches on issues related to online discourse and language use, which could fall under cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of its findings for promoting healthier exchanges in digital public spheres, which could fall under cs.SOC (Computational Social Science).
